{"title_page": "Pink robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of songbird native to southeastern Australia}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Pink robin\n| image = Pink Robin 2 - Mount Field National Park.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704825/0 |title=''Petroica rodinogaster'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| taxon = Petroica rodinogaster\n| authority = ([[Auguste Drapiez|Drapiez]], 1819)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''pink robin''' (''Petroica rodinogaster'') is a small [[passerine]] bird native to southeastern [[Australia]]. Its natural [[habitat]]s are cool temperate [[forest]]s of far southeastern Australia. Like many brightly coloured robins of the family [[Petroicidae]], it is [[Sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]]. Measuring  13.5&nbsp;cm (5.3&nbsp;in) in length, the robin has a small, thin, black bill, and dark brown eyes and legs. The male has a distinctive white forehead spot and pink breast, with grey-black upperparts, wings and tail. The belly is white. The female has grey-brown plumage. The position of the pink robin and its Australian relatives on the passerine family tree is unclear; the Petroicidae are not closely related to either the [[European robin|European]] or [[American robin]]s, but appear to be an early offshoot of the [[Passerida]] group of [[songbird]]s.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nDescribed by Belgian naturalist, [[Auguste Drapiez]], in 1819, the pink robin is a member of the Australasian robin family [[Petroicidae]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref><ref name=Boles35>{{cite book |title=The Robins and Flycatchers of Australia |last=Boles |first=Walter E.|year=1988 |publisher=Angus & Robertson |location=Sydney |isbn=0-207-15400-7|page=35}}</ref> [[Charles Sibley|Sibley]] and [[Jon Ahlquist|Ahlquist]]'s [[DNA-DNA hybridisation]] studies placed this group in a [[Corvida]] [[parvorder]] comprising many tropical and Australian passerines, including [[Pardalotidae|pardalotes]], [[Maluridae|fairy-wrens]], [[Meliphagidae|honeyeaters]], and crows.<ref name=\"SibAhl\">{{cite book|vauthors=Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE |title=Phylogeny and Classification of Birds: A Study in Molecular Evolution |publisher= Yale University Press|location=New Haven, CT|year=1990|pages=603, 610\u201327|isbn=0-300-04085-7}}</ref> However, subsequent molecular research (and current consensus) places the robins as a very early offshoot of the [[Passerida]] (or \"advanced\" songbirds) within the [[songbird]] lineage.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Barker, F. Keith |author2=Cibois, Alice |author3=Schikler, Peter A. |author4=Feinstein, Julie |author5=Cracraft, Joel  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2004|title=Phylogeny and diversification of the largest avian radiation |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|PNAS]] |volume=101 |issue=30 |pages=11040\u201345 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0401892101 |url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/0401892101v1.pdf |accessdate=2008-08-14 |pmid=15263073 |pmc=503738}}</ref> Testing of the nuclear and mitochondrial DNA of Australian members of the genus ''Petroica'' suggests that the pink and [[rose robin]]s are each other's closest relative within the genus.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes) |author1=Loynes, Kate |author2=Joseph, Leo |author3=Keogh, J. Scott |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=53|issue=1|pages=212\u201319|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012 |year=2009 |pmid=19463962}}</ref> \n\nThe generic name [[Petroica] derives from the Greek ''petros'' 'stone' and ''oikos'' 'house'. The specific name ''rodinogaster'' derives from the Greek ''rhodinos'' 'pink' and ''gaster'' 'belly'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|pages=162, 240|accessdate = 2020-04-07}}</ref>\n{{Listen\n|title=Male pink robin calling\n|filename=Petroica rodinogaster.ogg\n|pos=right\n|type=sound\n|help=no\n}}\n\n==Description==\nThe pink robin is 13.5&nbsp;cm (5.5&nbsp;in) long and displays [[sexual dimorphism]] \u2013 the males and females have [[plumage]] which differ markedly. The male has a dark blackish-grey head, throat, back, wings and tail, a pink breast and belly fading to white on the lower abdomen, and a white forehead. The female is dark grey-brown above, with two buff-coloured wing-bars and pinkish-tinged underparts. The bill and feet are black, and the eyes are dark brown.<ref name=Slater74>{{cite book |title=A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines |last=Slater |first=Peter|year=1974 |publisher=Rigby |location=Adelaide |isbn=0-85179-813-6|page=171}}</ref>\n[[File:Pink-robin.jpg|thumb|left|260px|Pink Robin, [[Tasmania]]]]\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nIts range is forests of southern Victoria and neighbouring parts of South Australia and New South Wales, and Tasmania.<ref name=Slater74/>\n\n==Breeding==\nBreeding occurs from September to January. The nest is a well-made, neat, deep cup of moss. [[Spider web]]s, feathers and fur are used for binding or filling, and the nest is generally placed in a tree fork up to 5&nbsp;m (15&nbsp;ft) above the ground. A clutch of three or four eggs is laid. The eggs, which measure 18 by 14&nbsp;mm, are greyish-, greenish- or blueish-white, and are marked with dark brown and lavender splotches and spots, usually concentrated around the large end.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Beruldsen  | first = Gordon  | title = Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs  | publisher = self  | year = 2003  | location = Kenmore Hills, Qld  | page = 340 | doi = | isbn = 0-646-42798-9}}</ref>\n\n==Feeding==\nPrey consists of a variety of spiders and insects, including caterpillars, [[ichneumon wasp]]s, beetles, flies and ants.<ref name=\"Barker 1984\">{{cite book |vauthors=Barker RD, Vestjens WJ | year = 1984 | title = ''The Food of Australian Birds: (II) Passerines | publisher = Melbourne University Press | isbn = 0-643-05115-5 | page = 53}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1067859}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, pink}}\n[[Category:Petroica|pink robin]]\n[[Category:Robins|pink robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1819|pink robin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of songbird native to southeastern Australia}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Pink robin\n| image = Pink Robin 2 - Mount Field National Park.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704825/0 |title=''Petroica rodinogaster'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| taxon = Petroica rodinogaster\n| authority = ([[Auguste Drapiez|Drapiez]], 1819)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''pink robin''' (''Petroica rodinogaster'') is a small [[passerine]] bird native to southeastern [[Australia]]. Its natural [[habitat]]s are cool temperate [[forest]]s of far southeastern Australia. Like many brightly coloured robins of the family [[Petroicidae]], it is [[Sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]]. Measuring  13.5&nbsp;cm (5.3&nbsp;in) in length, the robin has a small, thin, black bill, and dark brown eyes and legs. The male has a distinctive white forehead spot and pink breast, with grey-black upperparts, wings and tail. The belly is white. The female has grey-brown plumage. The position of the pink robin and its Australian relatives on the passerine family tree is unclear; the Petroicidae are not closely related to either the [[European robin|European]] or [[American robin]]s, but appear to be an early offshoot of the [[Passerida]] group of [[songbird]]s.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nDescribed by Belgian naturalist, [[Auguste Drapiez]], in 1819, the pink robin is a member of the Australasian robin family [[Petroicidae]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref><ref name=Boles35>{{cite book |title=The Robins and Flycatchers of Australia |last=Boles |first=Walter E.|year=1988 |publisher=Angus & Robertson |location=Sydney |isbn=0-207-15400-7|page=35}}</ref> [[Charles Sibley|Sibley]] and [[Jon Ahlquist|Ahlquist]]'s [[DNA-DNA hybridisation]] studies placed this group in a [[Corvida]] [[parvorder]] comprising many tropical and Australian passerines, including [[Pardalotidae|pardalotes]], [[Maluridae|fairy-wrens]], [[Meliphagidae|honeyeaters]], and crows.<ref name=\"SibAhl\">{{cite book|vauthors=Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE |title=Phylogeny and Classification of Birds: A Study in Molecular Evolution |publisher= Yale University Press|location=New Haven, CT|year=1990|pages=603, 610\u201327|isbn=0-300-04085-7}}</ref> However, subsequent molecular research (and current consensus) places the robins as a very early offshoot of the [[Passerida]] (or \"advanced\" songbirds) within the [[songbird]] lineage.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Barker, F. Keith |author2=Cibois, Alice |author3=Schikler, Peter A. |author4=Feinstein, Julie |author5=Cracraft, Joel  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2004|title=Phylogeny and diversification of the largest avian radiation |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|PNAS]] |volume=101 |issue=30 |pages=11040\u201345 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0401892101 |url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/0401892101v1.pdf |accessdate=2008-08-14 |pmid=15263073 |pmc=503738}}</ref> Testing of the nuclear and mitochondrial DNA of Australian members of the genus ''Petroica'' suggests that the pink and [[rose robin]]s are each other's closest relative within the genus.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes) |author1=Loynes, Kate |author2=Joseph, Leo |author3=Keogh, J. Scott |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=53|issue=1|pages=212\u201319|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012 |year=2009 |pmid=19463962}}</ref> \n\nThe generic name [[''Petroica'']] derives from the Greek ''petros'' 'stone' and ''oikos'' 'house'. The specific name ''rodinogaster'' derives from the Greek ''rhodinos'' 'pink' and ''gaster'' 'belly'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|pages=162, 240|accessdate = 2020-04-07}}</ref>\n{{Listen\n|title=Male pink robin calling\n|filename=Petroica rodinogaster.ogg\n|pos=right\n|type=sound\n|help=no\n}}\n\n==Description==\nThe pink robin is 13.5&nbsp;cm (5.5&nbsp;in) long and displays [[sexual dimorphism]] \u2013 the males and females have [[plumage]] which differ markedly. The male has a dark blackish-grey head, throat, back, wings and tail, a pink breast and belly fading to white on the lower abdomen, and a white forehead. The female is dark grey-brown above, with two buff-coloured wing-bars and pinkish-tinged underparts. The bill and feet are black, and the eyes are dark brown.<ref name=Slater74>{{cite book |title=A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines |last=Slater |first=Peter|year=1974 |publisher=Rigby |location=Adelaide |isbn=0-85179-813-6|page=171}}</ref>\n[[File:Pink-robin.jpg|thumb|left|260px|Pink Robin, [[Tasmania]]]]\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nIts range is forests of southern Victoria and neighbouring parts of South Australia and New South Wales, and Tasmania.<ref name=Slater74/>\n\n==Breeding==\nBreeding occurs from September to January. The nest is a well-made, neat, deep cup of moss. [[Spider web]]s, feathers and fur are used for binding or filling, and the nest is generally placed in a tree fork up to 5&nbsp;m (15&nbsp;ft) above the ground. A clutch of three or four eggs is laid. The eggs, which measure 18 by 14&nbsp;mm, are greyish-, greenish- or blueish-white, and are marked with dark brown and lavender splotches and spots, usually concentrated around the large end.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Beruldsen  | first = Gordon  | title = Australian Birds: Their Nests and Eggs  | publisher = self  | year = 2003  | location = Kenmore Hills, Qld  | page = 340 | doi = | isbn = 0-646-42798-9}}</ref>\n\n==Feeding==\nPrey consists of a variety of spiders and insects, including caterpillars, [[ichneumon wasp]]s, beetles, flies and ants.<ref name=\"Barker 1984\">{{cite book |vauthors=Barker RD, Vestjens WJ | year = 1984 | title = ''The Food of Australian Birds: (II) Passerines | publisher = Melbourne University Press | isbn = 0-643-05115-5 | page = 53}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1067859}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, pink}}\n[[Category:Petroica|pink robin]]\n[[Category:Robins|pink robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1819|pink robin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pink_robin"}
{"title_page": "Hopekshannon/Collaborative learning", "text_new": "=== Contents ===\n\u2022\t1Theoretical background\n\u2022\t2Differences from cooperative learning\n\u2022\t3Collaborative learning approaches \n\u2022\t4Environments for learning \no\tClassroom\no\tWorkplace\n\n=== Theoretical background ===\n[edit source]\nCollaborative learning is rooted in Lev Vygotsky's concept of learning called zone of proximal development. Typically there are tasks that learners can and cannot accomplish. Between these two areas is the zone of proximal development, which is a category of things that a learner can learn but with the help of guidance. The zone of proximal development gives guidance as to what set of skills a learner has that are in the process of maturation. In Vygotsky's definition of zone of proximal development, he highlighted the importance of learning through communication and interactions with others rather than just through independent work.[10] This has made way for the ideas of group learning, one of which being collaborative learning.\nKenneth Bruffee recently studied the roots of collaborative learning and was able to trace some applications of collaborative learning back to the 1970s.<ref>Bruffee, K. A. (1999). Collaborative learning: Higher education, interdependence, and the authority of knowledge. Johns Hopkins University Press, 2715 North Charles Street, Baltimore, MD 21218-4363.</ref> Traditional teaching strategies were not meeting the educational needs of the new college student population that began attending school after the open-door policies of the time. During Bruffee\u2019s research, he concluded to give credit to M. L. J. Abercrombie for creating the collaborative learning and peer-editing techniques. In her published work, The Anatomy of Judgment, she stated that medical students would not be able to successfully make an accurate diagnostic judgment without collaborative learning. Other theorists and professors before the 1970s had made adjustments in their teaching and classroom preparation in order to meet the needs of students. Collaborative styles of learning were also evident in the late 1700s and early 1800s. George Jardine, a professor of logic and philosophy at the University of Glasgow, wanted to implement a new style of learning in his class due to the social and political changes. He decided to use peer-editing as a form of collaborative learning to help improve his classroom techniques. <ref>Gaillet, L. L. (1992). A Foreshadowing of Modern Theories and Practices of Collaborative Learning: The Work of Scottish Rhetorician George Jardine.</ref> \n\n=== Differences from cooperative learning ===\n[edit source]\nThere has been a split regarding the differences between collaborative and cooperative learning. Some believe that collaborative learning is similar to, yet distinct from, cooperative learning. While both models use a division of labor, collaborative learning requires the mutual engagement of all participants and a coordinated effort to solve the problem. Whereas cooperative learning requires individuals to take responsibility for a specific section and then coordinate their respective parts together.[13] Another proposed differentiation is that cooperative learning is typically used for children because it is used to understand the foundations of knowledge while collaborative learning applies to college and university students because it is used to teach non-foundations of learning. Another believed difference is that collaborative learning is a philosophy of interaction whereas cooperative learning is a structure of interaction.[14]\nHowever, many psychologists have defined cooperative learning and collaborative learning similarly. Both are group learning mechanisms for learners to obtain a set of skills or knowledge. The two styles of learning have resulted in similar beneficial outcomes.<ref>Tolmie, A. K., Topping, K. J., Christie, D., Donaldson, C., Howe, C., Jessiman, E., ... & Thurston, A. (2010). Social effects of collaborative learning in primary schools. Learning and instruction, 20(3), 177-191.</ref> Some notable psychologists that use this definition for both collaborative and cooperative learning are Johnson & Johnson, Slavin, Cooper and more.\n\n=== Collaborative learning approaches ===\n \nMain article: collaborative: a sourcebook\nThere are a wide variety of learning techniques that fall under the umbrella of collaborative learning. These can take place in-class and out-of-class, through technology, or in person. Each collaborative activity has a different process and/or goal to complete within a group. People can be organized in small or large groups depending on the learning approach. Some studies argue a few of the learning approaches are separate from collaborative learning and are unique learning concepts. \n\nThe relationship between collaborative learning and cooperative learning, as previously stated, is controversial. Some suggest cooperative learning is a collaborative activity. \nCooperative learning methods vary in explanation, but overall cooperative learning ensures each participant works on a portion of the assignment to collectively complete it.<ref>Davidson, N., & Major, C. H. (2014). Boundary crossings: Cooperative learning, collaborative learning, and problem-based learning. Journal on excellence in college teaching, 25.</ref> For instance, a group could assign each member a specific job to complete for a class project. This technique gives each student a personal responsibility and one for their entire group. \n\nAnother popular technique in an educational setting is problem-centered instruction, which is used to direct. It is used to direct participants through a collaboration task. Instructions are implicated to guide team members, individually and all together. Problem-centered instruction is a tool used in a variety of collaborative learning techniques. Instructions promote students\u2019 engaged activity, because it involves timely progression. This technique also involves real-world application for participants to apply their problem-solving skills.<ref>Merrill, M. D., & Gilbert, C. G. (2008). Effective peer interaction in a problem-centered instructional strategy. Distance Education, 29(2), 199-206. Retrieved from http://byui.idm.oclc.org/login?url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/217787799?accountid=9817</ref>  \n\nIn the late 1960s guided design was developed. This learning technique focuses on using problem-centered instruction in a small group discussion with a step by step process. An open-ended question is proposed to the group and then the question is split into the following sections: (1) Define the situation and problem, (2) State the desired outcome/ goal, (3) Develop a solution or multiple, (4) Assess and evaluate the solution(s), (5) and Create a detailed plan. Participants are encouraged to follow these steps in a sequential order. Between each step, the proposed idea must be presented to a professional (teacher, leader, faculty, etc.). The professional will then give the team feedback for the group to make adjustments in the necessary area(s). The goal is for each member to have the opportunity to share ideas and receive constructive criticism in return. As a team they will resolve differences of opinion and work towards a consensus of opinion. This will aid their ability to practice social skills, communication skills, and collaboration skills. Guided Design is most commonly used in engineering, pharmacy, science programs, nursing, and liberal arts, but is also effectively practiced in other areas of education. \n\nIn the past few decades problem-centered Instruction has been a popular form of learning in medical education. In the 1950s Abercrombie examined the benefits of collaborative learning in the medical field. She concluded that students who worked in teams were able to make more accurate judgements on a case, as opposed to working individually. Many universities adopted problem-centered instruction in their medical fields. In 1985, Harvard Medical School created a new curriculum called \u201cNew Pathways\u201d that is based off of problem-center instruction. Problem-centered instruction has since then spread to other colleges.<ref>Alhaj, A. A. Y. (2014). The Effectiveness of Collaborative Learning in Improving Tertiary Students' Communicative Competence (A case Study of Medical Students at Jazan University, Kingdom Saudi Arabia (Doctoral dissertation, University of Gezira).</ref>\n\nWriting groups (also known as peer response groups, helping circles, and class criticism) is a technique that involves collaborative learning before writing papers and afterward. Groups will come together to share each other\u2019s theses and accumulate ideas for their writing prompts. Then students break away from the group and contrast their written essays. After drafts are completed, the writing group gathers, and individuals are able to receive verbal and written feedback on their draft papers. Most students learn from this learning tactic, because they can collect diverse perspectives from their team members. The environment invites a discussion about small- or large-scale dilemmas that can be research-based or solely based on beliefs/ opinions from personal experience.<ref>Lee, A., & Boud, D. (2003). Writing groups, change and academic identity: Research development as local practice. Studies in higher education, 28(2), 187-200.</ref> This learning style has proven to be very effective in high school and college level English courses. \n \nIt is common for learners to help one another to understand the concepts they struggle with. This can take place in a standard classroom setting when one student asks a nearby peer for assistance or clarification on a topic/ issue. This traditional collaborative learning approach is peer teaching. The McGill University expanded upon peer teaching and developed a systematic procedure. To moderate the study teaching, the university created four of the following focus study groups: research-oriented, expression-oriented, appreciation-oriented, and experience-oriented.<ref>Brady, E. M., Holt, S. R., & Welt, B. (2003). Peer teaching in lifelong learning institutes. Educational Gerontology, 29(10), 851-868.</ref> In this procedure, students form one-on-one pairs called \u201clearning cells\u201d. Each learning cell will help each other in the classroom and out of the classroom. They will focus on completing assignments, teaching each other difficult concepts they struggle with, and help one another prepare for upcoming exams. Research has compared the learning cell technique to other learning styles and the McGill students who applied learning cells triumphed over students who used other learning approaches, such as seminars and discussions.<ref>Goodsell, A. S. (1992). Collaborative learning: A sourcebook for higher education.</ref> \n\nIn the late 1980s another form of peer teaching evolved in mathematic education and math workshops. This learning style was developed at the University of California at Berkeley by Uri Treisman. He wanted to confront the issues with previous tutoring programs, specifically for different ethnic groups taking introductory calculus. Treisman created an improved model that concentrated on peer teaching to help the overall student population succeed.<ref>Dick, T., Stone, T., Firor, K., & Cavinato, A. G. (2002). Excel: peer teaching in collaborative Groups. In Proceeding of STEMTEC conference pathways to Change, April (pp. 19-20).</ref> He named it \u201cProfessional Development Program\u201d. The math workshops would be led by a professional instructor, usually a graduate, who would help a small group of students solve problems. The instructors encouraged peer teaching within the group. Mathematic workshops promote students to engage in collaborative activities as teachers and learners rather than individuals competing against each other to improve content knowledge. \n\nDiscussion groups and seminars are very well-known collaborative activity that relies on communication skills throughout the group. Often times the group will be presented with a prompt or question to begin the discussion. When the discussion is student led, the conversation heavily depends on the effort and comments of the group. However, in some instances an instructor may interfere to guide the conversation in a desired direction. Compared to all of the collaborative learning approaches previously explained, discussion groups and seminars are the activities with the most freedom given to participants. There is an abundance of possible discussion formats and strategies that are designed to create an environment for people to freely share their opinions and ideas about an assigned topic.<ref>Goodsell, A. S. (1992). Collaborative learning: A sourcebook for higher education.</ref>\n\n[[User:Hopekshannon|Hopekshannon]] ([[User talk:Hopekshannon|talk]]) 04:42, 8 April 2020 (UTC)\n", "text_old": "=== Contents ===\n\u2022\t1Theoretical background\n\u2022\t2Differences from cooperative learning\n\u2022\t3Collaborative learning approaches \n\u2022\t4Environments for learning \no\tClassroom\no\tWorkplace\n\n=== Theoretical background ===\n[edit source]\nCollaborative learning is rooted in Lev Vygotsky's concept of learning called zone of proximal development. Typically there are tasks that learners can and cannot accomplish. Between these two areas is the zone of proximal development, which is a category of things that a learner can learn but with the help of guidance. The zone of proximal development gives guidance as to what set of skills a learner has that are in the process of maturation. In Vygotsky's definition of zone of proximal development, he highlighted the importance of learning through communication and interactions with others rather than just through independent work.[10] This has made way for the ideas of group learning, one of which being collaborative learning.\nKenneth Bruffee recently studied the roots of collaborative learning and was able to trace some applications of collaborative learning back to the 1970s.<ref>Bruffee, K. A. (1999). Collaborative learning: Higher education, interdependence, and the authority of knowledge. Johns Hopkins University Press, 2715 North Charles Street, Baltimore, MD 21218-4363.</ref> Traditional teaching strategies were not meeting the educational needs of the new college student population that began attending school after the open-door policies of the time. During Bruffee\u2019s research, he concluded to give credit to M. L. J. Abercrombie for creating the collaborative learning and peer-editing techniques. In her published work, The Anatomy of Judgment, she stated that medical students would not be able to successfully make an accurate diagnostic judgment without collaborative learning. Other theorists and professors before the 1970s had made adjustments in their teaching and classroom preparation in order to meet the needs of students. Collaborative styles of learning were also evident in the late 1700s and early 1800s. George Jardine, a professor of logic and philosophy at the University of Glasgow, wanted to implement a new style of learning in his class due to the social and political changes. He decided to use peer-editing as a form of collaborative learning to help improve his classroom techniques. <ref>Gaillet, L. L. (1992). A Foreshadowing of Modern Theories and Practices of Collaborative Learning: The Work of Scottish Rhetorician George Jardine.</ref> \n\n=== Differences from cooperative learning ===\n[edit source]\nThere has been a split regarding the differences between collaborative and cooperative learning. Some believe that collaborative learning is similar to, yet distinct from, cooperative learning. While both models use a division of labor, collaborative learning requires the mutual engagement of all participants and a coordinated effort to solve the problem. Whereas cooperative learning requires individuals to take responsibility for a specific section and then coordinate their respective parts together.[13] Another proposed differentiation is that cooperative learning is typically used for children because it is used to understand the foundations of knowledge while collaborative learning applies to college and university students because it is used to teach non-foundations of learning. Another believed difference is that collaborative learning is a philosophy of interaction whereas cooperative learning is a structure of interaction.[14]\nHowever, many psychologists have defined cooperative learning and collaborative learning similarly. Both are group learning mechanisms for learners to obtain a set of skills or knowledge. The two styles of learning have resulted in similar beneficial outcomes.<ref>Tolmie, A. K., Topping, K. J., Christie, D., Donaldson, C., Howe, C., Jessiman, E., ... & Thurston, A. (2010). Social effects of collaborative learning in primary schools. Learning and instruction, 20(3), 177-191.</ref> Some notable psychologists that use this definition for both collaborative and cooperative learning are Johnson & Johnson, Slavin, Cooper and more.\n\n=== Collaborative learning approaches ===\n \nMain article: collaborative: a sourcebook\nThere are a wide variety of learning techniques that fall under the umbrella of collaborative learning. These can take place in-class and out-of-class, through technology, or in person. Each collaborative activity has a different process and/or goal to complete within a group. People can be organized in small or large groups depending on the learning approach. Some studies argue a few of the learning approaches are separate from collaborative learning and are unique learning concepts. \n\nThe relationship between collaborative learning and cooperative learning, as previously stated, is controversial. Some suggest cooperative learning is a collaborative activity. \nCooperative learning methods vary in explanation, but overall cooperative learning ensures each participant works on a portion of the assignment to collectively complete it.<ref>Davidson, N., & Major, C. H. (2014). Boundary crossings: Cooperative learning, collaborative learning, and problem-based learning. Journal on excellence in college teaching, 25.</ref> For instance, a group could assign each member a specific job to complete for a class project. This technique gives each student a personal responsibility and one for their entire group. \n\nAnother popular technique in an educational setting is problem-centered instruction, which is used to direct. It is used to direct participants through a collaboration task. Instructions are implicated to guide team members, individually and all together. Problem-centered instruction is a tool used in a variety of collaborative learning techniques. Instructions promote students\u2019 engaged activity, because it involves timely progression. This technique also involves real-world application for participants to apply their problem-solving skills.<ref>Merrill, M. D., & Gilbert, C. G. (2008). Effective peer interaction in a problem-centered instructional strategy. Distance Education, 29(2), 199-206. Retrieved from http://byui.idm.oclc.org/login?url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/217787799?accountid=9817</ref>  \n\nIn the late 1960s guided design was developed. This learning technique focuses on using problem-centered instruction in a small group discussion with a step by step process. An open-ended question is proposed to the group and then the question is split into the following sections: (1) Define the situation and problem, (2) State the desired outcome/ goal, (3) Develop a solution or multiple, (4) Asses and evaluate the solution(s), (5) and Create a detailed plan. Participants are encouraged to follow these steps in a sequential order. Between each step, the proposed idea must be presented to a professional (teacher, leader, faculty, etc.). The professional will then give the team feedback for the group to make adjustments in the necessary area(s). The goal is for each member to have the opportunity to share ideas and receive constructive criticism in return. As a team they will resolve differences of opinion and work towards a consensus of opinion. This will aid their ability to practice social skills, communication skills, and collaboration skills. Guided Design is most commonly used in engineering, pharmacy, science programs, nursing, and liberal arts, but is also effectively practiced in other areas of education. \n\nIn the past few decades problem-centered Instruction has been a popular form of learning in medical education. In the 1950s Abercrombie examined the benefits of collaborative learning in the medical field. She concluded that students who worked in teams were able to make more accurate judgements on a case, as opposed to working individually. Many universities adopted problem-centered instruction in their medical fields. In 1985, Harvard Medical School created a new curriculum called \u201cNew Pathways\u201d that is based off of problem-center instruction. Problem-centered instruction has since then spread to other colleges.<ref>Alhaj, A. A. Y. (2014). The Effectiveness of Collaborative Learning in Improving Tertiary Students' Communicative Competence (A case Study of Medical Students at Jazan University, Kingdom Saudi Arabia (Doctoral dissertation, University of Gezira).</ref>\n\nWriting groups (also known as peer response groups, helping circles, and class criticism) is a technique that involves collaborative learning before writing papers and afterward. Groups will come together to share each other\u2019s theses and accumulate ideas for their writing prompts. Then students break away from the group and contrast their written essays. After drafts are completed, the writing group gathers, and individuals are able to receive verbal and written feedback on their draft papers. Most students learn from this learning tactic, because they can collect diverse perspectives from their team members. The environment invites a discussion about small- or large-scale dilemmas that can be research-based or solely based on beliefs/ opinions from personal experience.<ref>Lee, A., & Boud, D. (2003). Writing groups, change and academic identity: Research development as local practice. Studies in higher education, 28(2), 187-200.</ref> This learning style has proven to be very effective in high school and college level English courses. \n \nIt is common for learners to help one another to understand the concepts they struggle with. This can take place in a standard classroom setting when one student asks a nearby peer for assistance or clarification on a topic/ issue. This traditional collaborative learning approach is peer teaching. The McGill University expanded upon peer teaching and developed a systematic procedure. To moderate the study teaching, the university created four of the following focus study groups: research-oriented, expression-oriented, appreciation-oriented, and experience-oriented.<ref>Brady, E. M., Holt, S. R., & Welt, B. (2003). Peer teaching in lifelong learning institutes. Educational Gerontology, 29(10), 851-868.</ref> In this procedure, students form one-on-one pairs called \u201clearning cells\u201d. Each learning cell will help each other in the classroom and out of the classroom. They will focus on completing assignments, teaching each other difficult concepts they struggle with, and help one another prepare for upcoming exams. Research has compared the learning cell technique to other learning styles and the McGill students who applied learning cells triumphed over students who used other learning approaches, such as seminars and discussions.<ref>Goodsell, A. S. (1992). Collaborative learning: A sourcebook for higher education.</ref> \n\nIn the late 1980s another form of peer teaching evolved in mathematic education and math workshops. This learning style was developed at the University of California at Berkeley by Uri Treisman. He wanted to confront the issues with previous tutoring programs, specifically for different ethnic groups taking introductory calculus. Treisman created an improved model that concentrated on peer teaching to help the overall student population succeed.<ref>Dick, T., Stone, T., Firor, K., & Cavinato, A. G. (2002). Excel: peer teaching in collaborative Groups. In Proceeding of STEMTEC conference pathways to Change, April (pp. 19-20).</ref> He named it \u201cProfessional Development Program\u201d. The math workshops would be led by a professional instructor, usually a graduate, who would help a small group of students solve problems. The instructors encouraged peer teaching within the group. Mathematic workshops promote students to engage in collaborative activities as teachers and learners rather than individuals competing against each other to improve content knowledge. \n\nDiscussion groups and seminars are very well-known collaborative activity that relies on communication skills throughout the group. Often times the group will be presented with a prompt or question to begin the discussion. When the discussion is student led, the conversation heavily depends on the effort and comments of the group. However, in some instances an instructor may interfere to guide the conversation in a desired direction. Compared to all of the collaborative learning approaches previously explained, discussion groups and seminars are the activities with the most freedom given to participants. There is an abundance of possible discussion formats and strategies that are designed to create an environment for people to freely share their opinions and ideas about an assigned topic.<ref>Goodsell, A. S. (1992). Collaborative learning: A sourcebook for higher education.</ref>\n\n[[User:Hopekshannon|Hopekshannon]] ([[User talk:Hopekshannon|talk]]) 04:42, 8 April 2020 (UTC)\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "bray", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hopekshannon/Collaborative_learning"}
{"title_page": "George Iles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga Football Club\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 21\n|ru_appearances1     =14\n|ru_tries1           =7\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =21\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tauranga)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = 26\n|ru_appearances2     =\n|ru_tries2           =2\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =6 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tauranga)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =8\n|ru_triesA           =7\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =21\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = \n|ru_appearancesC     = 1\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =3\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = 2\n|tries3              = 1\n|goals3              = 0\n|fieldgoals3         =0\n|points3             = 3\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = [[Bay of Plenty rugby league team|Bay of Plenty]]\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            =  \n|appearancesC        = 2\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League Days===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn the 16th of September history was made in Tauranga with the first ever game of rugby keague played there. Tauranga took on the Rotorua team on the Tauranga Domain. As well as George Iles playing, David Borell and Arthur Iles also played in the match. Rotorua won a high scoring match 29-28 with both Iles and Borell scoring tries\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rotorua Wins by One Point\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8092\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220918.2.24\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nA game against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] was also arranged which was a remarkable achievement in itself given that rugby league was not even played in the area until a month earlier. The match was between New South Wales and Bay of Plenty. George Iles naturally played and the team also featured future Kiwi [[George Gardiner (rugby league)|George Gardiner]] while the visiting NSW team featured the likes of [[Frank Burge]] and [[Reg Latta]]. New South Wales won the match 29 points to 5 with Borell scoring a try and Joseph Rogers kicking a goal for the local team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kangaroos 29 Bay of Plenty 5\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8101\n| date = 1922-09-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220928.2.33\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga again made history by playing in the first ever rugby league game in [[Te Puke]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from throughout the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On October 14 Tauranga played a match on the Waihi Recreation Ground and lost 6-19 in front of a large attendance, Iles again leading the Tauranga team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Waihi-Tauranga League Match\n| page =2\n| publisher =Waihi Daily Telegraph, Volume XX, Issue 6741\n| date = 1922-10-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WHDT19221016.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. These efforts to grow the game in the area, while somewhat remarkable, ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in Te Puke and then again in the return match in Tauranga. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played for Tauranga against Te Puke in a Kusab's Cup match won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played another match for them against Te Puke in June 1925, and captained Tauranga against [[Rangitaiki]] in 1925 to a 12-5 victory with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was playing for the Cadets Old Boys club this season\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga Football Club\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 21\n|ru_appearances1     =14\n|ru_tries1           =7\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =21\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tauranga)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = 26\n|ru_appearances2     =\n|ru_tries2           =2\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =6 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tauranga)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =8\n|ru_triesA           =7\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =21\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = \n|ru_appearancesC     = 1\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =3\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = 2\n|tries3              = 1\n|goals3              = 0\n|fieldgoals3         =0\n|points3             = 3\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = Bay of Plenty\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            =  \n|appearancesC        = 2\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League Days===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn the 16th of September history was made in Tauranga with the first ever game of rugby keague played there. Tauranga took on the Rotorua team on the Tauranga Domain. As well as George Iles playing, David Borell and Arthur Iles also played in the match. Rotorua won a high scoring match 29-28 with both Iles and Borell scoring tries\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rotorua Wins by One Point\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8092\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220918.2.24\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nA game against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] was also arranged which was a remarkable achievement in itself given that rugby league was not even played in the area until a month earlier. The match was between New South Wales and Bay of Plenty. George Iles naturally played and the team also featured future Kiwi [[George Gardiner (rugby league)|George Gardiner]] while the visiting NSW team featured the likes of [[Frank Burge]] and [[Reg Latta]]. New South Wales won the match 29 points to 5 with Borell scoring a try and Joseph Rogers kicking a goal for the local team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kangaroos 29 Bay of Plenty 5\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8101\n| date = 1922-09-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220928.2.33\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga again made history by playing in the first ever rugby league game in [[Te Puke]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from throughout the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On October 14 Tauranga played a match on the Waihi Recreation Ground and lost 6-19 in front of a large attendance, Iles again leading the Tauranga team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Waihi-Tauranga League Match\n| page =2\n| publisher =Waihi Daily Telegraph, Volume XX, Issue 6741\n| date = 1922-10-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WHDT19221016.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. These efforts to grow the game in the area, while somewhat remarkable, ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in Te Puke and then again in the return match in Tauranga. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played for Tauranga against Te Puke in a Kusab's Cup match won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played another match for them against Te Puke in June 1925, and captained Tauranga against [[Rangitaiki]] in 1925 to a 12-5 victory with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was playing for the Cadets Old Boys club this season\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Iles"}
{"title_page": "David J. Rodger", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2014}}\n'''David J. Rodger''' (August 30, 1970 in [[Newcastle Upon Tyne]] &ndash; November 22, 2015 in [[Bristol]]) was a British author and game designer best known for his novels set in a near-future world of corporate and political intrigue. He published nine novels, all set in the same universe, both before and after an apocalyptic event. ''[[Oakfield (novel)|Oakfield]]'', ''[[God Seed (novel)|God Seed]]'', ''[[Dante\u2019s Fool (novel)|Dante's Fool]]'', ''[[Iron Man Project (novel)|Iron Man Project]]'', ''[[Edge (novel)|Edge]]'' and ''[[Living in Flames (novel)|Living in Flames]]'' are all near-future supernatural thrillers, while ''[[Dog Eat Dog (novel)|Dog Eat Dog]]'', ''[[The Black Lake (novel)|The Black Lake]]'' and ''[[The Social Club (novel)|The Social Club]]'', are based in the world of ''[[Yellow Dawn]]'', a [[role-playing game]] set in the same future world ten years after it has been devastated by a terrible mutagenic virus.\n[[File:David J. Rodger.jpg|thumb]]\nRodger's novels combined high-tech intrigue and political/corporate machinations with elements of the [[Cthulhu Mythos]], as created by [[H.P. Lovecraft]]. Rodger's contributions to the Mythos include the creation of several new [[Great Old One]]s in his novels ''Edge'', ''Dog Eat Dog'' and ''Living in Flames'' and the use of the [[Outer God]] [[Nyarlathotep]] in the novel [[God Seed (novel)|God Seed]]. In [[Yellow Dawn]], Rodger's interpretation of the Mythos, in particular the Great Old One [[Hastur]], is a major part of the background material. Rodger also published [[Shadows of the Quantinex]], a large-scale campaign expansion for the Yellow Dawn game, and released a 2.5 Edition update to the basic game in 2013. At the time of his death in 2015, Rodger was known to have completed a 3rd Edition of the game, bringing it in line with the latest edition of the Call of Cthulhu rules system, to be published through [[Modiphius Entertainment]].<ref>http://www.modiphius.com/</ref>\n\nRodger also wrote ''[[Cloudy Head]]'', a children's story illustrated by [[Kenn-Ole Moen]], and ''[[Murder at Sharky Point]]'', a [[murder mystery game]].\n\nRodger started writing at the age of 19. He spent 8 years working for the Environment Agency (non-departmental government agency), developing a virtual communications service within the IT Division, before moving into commercial project management for a major UK publisher. In 2000 Rodger's presence on the Internet got him a place in the BBC documentary ''[[Through The Eyes of the Young]]'', directed by Chris Terrill.\n\nRodger died at his home in Bristol on Sunday, November 22, 2015, after a short illness.<ref>http://brsbkblog.blogspot.co.uk/2015/11/sad-news-david-j-rodger-1970-2015.html</ref> Rodger is survived by his sister and his longtime girlfriend.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n*''God Seed'' (1996)\n*''Dante's Fool'' (1999)\n*''Iron Man Project'' (2005)\n*''Edge'' (2008)\n*''Dog Eat Dog'' (2010)\n*''Living in Flames'' (2012)\n*''The Black Lake'' (2012)\n*''The Social Club'' (2013)\n*''Oakfield'' (2015)\n\n===Collections===\n*''Songs of Spheres'' (2012)\n\n===Anthologies===\n*''Achtung! Cthulhu: Dark Tales of the Secret War'', edited by John Houlihan (Modiphius, 2015)\n\n===Games===\n*''Yellow Dawn'' 1st Edition (2006)\n*''Murder at Sharky Point'' (2007)\n*''Yellow Dawn'' 2nd Edition (2008)\n*''Shadows of the Quantinex'' (2009)\n*''Yellow Dawn'' 2.5 Edition (2012)\n\n===Children's Stories===\n*''Cloudy Head'' (Illustrated, 2007)\n\n===Scripts===\n*''Salo IV'' (2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidjrodger.com David J. Rodger official website]\n* [http://www.sfx.co.uk/2009/11/18/interview_with_self_published_writer_david_j_rodger Interview with David J Rodger, by SFX Magazine] (page now removed)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151126174241/http://www.thomasdavidparker.com/for-david/ Tribute to David J Rodger by Thomas David Parker] (page now removed)\n* [https://hierath.wordpress.com/2015/11/24/david-j-rodger-1970-2015/ Tribute to David J Rodger by Joanne Hall]\n* [http://www.thesprezz.com/post/133843733218/david-j-rodger-dies-at-45-the-writer-david-j Tribute to David J Rodger by design agency The Sprezz]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodger, David J.}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:British horror writers]]\n[[Category:British thriller writers]]\n[[Category:Cthulhu Mythos writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2014}}\n'''David J. Rodger''' (August 30, 1970 in [[Newcastle Upon Tyne]] &ndash; November 22, 2015 in [[Bristol]]) was a British author and game designer best known for his novels set in a near-future world of corporate and political intrigue. He published nine novels, all set in the same universe, both before and after an apocalyptic event. ''[[Oakfield (novel)|Oakfield]]'', ''[[God Seed (novel)|God Seed]]'', ''[[Dante\u2019s Fool (novel)|Dante's Fool]]'', ''[[Iron Man Project (novel)|Iron Man Project]]'', ''[[Edge (novel)|Edge]]'' and ''[[Living in Flames (novel)|Living in Flames]]'' are all near-future supernatural thrillers, while ''[[Dog Eat Dog (novel)|Dog Eat Dog]]'', ''[[The Black Lake (novel)|The Black Lake]]'' and ''[[The Social Club (novel)|The Social Club]]'', are based in the world of ''[[Yellow Dawn]]'', a [[role-playing game]] set in the same future world ten years after it has been devastated by a terrible mutagenic virus.\n[[File:David J. Rodger.jpg|thumb]]\nRodger's novels combined high-tech intrigue and political/corporate machinations with elements of the [[Cthulhu Mythos]], as created by [[H.P. Lovecraft]]. Rodger's contributions to the Mythos include the creation of several new [[Great Old One]]s in his novels ''Edge'', ''Dog Eat Dog'' and ''Living in Flames'' and the use of the [[Outer God]] [[Nyarlathotep]] in the novel [[God Seed (novel)|God Seed]]. In [[Yellow Dawn]], Rodger's interpretation of the Mythos, in particular the Great Old One [[Hastur]], is a major part of the background material. Rodger also published [[Shadows of the Quantinex]], a large-scale campaign expansion for the Yellow Dawn game, and released a 2.5 Edition update to the basic game in 2013. At the time of his death in 2015, Rodger was known to have completed a 3rd Edition of the game, bringing it in line with the latest edition of the Call of Cthulhu rules system, to be published through [[Modiphius Entertainment]].<ref>http://www.modiphius.com/</ref>\n\nRodger also wrote ''[[Cloudy Head]]'', a children's story illustrated by [[Kenn-Ole Moen]], and ''[[Murder at Sharky Point]]'', a [[murder mystery game]].\n\nRodger started writing at the age of 19. He spent 8 years working for the Environment Agency (non-departmental government agency), developing a virtual communications service within the IT Division, before moving into commercial project management for a major UK publisher. In 2000 Rodger's presence on the Internet got him a place in the BBC documentary ''[[Through The Eyes of the Young]]'', directed by Chris Terrill.\n\nRodger died at his home in Bristol on Sunday, November 22, 2015, after a short illness.<ref>http://brsbkblog.blogspot.co.uk/2015/11/sad-news-david-j-rodger-1970-2015.html</ref> Rodger is survived by his sister and his longtime girlfriend.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n*''God Seed'' (1996)\n*''Dante's Fool'' (1999)\n*''Iron Man Project'' (2005)\n*''Edge'' (2008)\n*''Dog Eat Dog'' (2010)\n*''Living in Flames'' (2012)\n*''The Black Lake'' (2012)\n*''The Social Club'' (2013)\n*''Oakfield'' (2015)\n\n===Collections===\n*''Songs of Spheres'' (2012)\n\n===Anthologies===\n*''Achtung! Cthulhu: Dark Tales of the Secret War'', edited by John Houlihan (Modiphius, 2015)\n\n===Games===\n*''Yellow Dawn'' 1st Edition (2006)\n*''Murder at Sharky Point'' (2007)\n*''Yellow Dawn'' 2nd Edition (2008)\n*''Shadows of the Quantinex'' (2009)\n*''Yellow Dawn'' 2.5 Edition (2012)\n\n===Children's Stories===\n*''Cloudy Head'' (Illustrated, 2007)\n\n===Scripts===\n*''Salo IV'' (2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidjrodger.com David J. Rodger official website]\n* [http://www.sfx.co.uk/2009/11/18/interview_with_self_published_writer_david_j_rodger Interview with David J Rodger, by SFX Magazine] (page now removed)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151126174241/http://www.thomasdavidparker.com/for-david/ Tribute to David J Rodger by Thomas David Parker] (page now removed)\n* [https://hierath.wordpress.com/2015/11/24/david-j-rodger-1970-2015/ Tribute to David J Rodger by Joanne Hall]\n* [http://www.thesprezz.com/post/133843733218/david-j-rodger-dies-at-45-the-writer-david-j Tribute to David J Rodger by design agency The Sprezz]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodger, David J.}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:British horror writers]]\n[[Category:British thriller writers]]\n[[Category:Cthulhu Mythos writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_J._Rodger"}
{"title_page": "K.P. Jayasankar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian documentary film director}}\n{{Use Indian English|date= March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = K.P. Jayasankar \n\n|image = {{CSS image crop\n|Image = The Director of the film \u201cSo Heddan, So Hoddan\u201d, K.P. Jayasankar addressing at the special screening of his film, during the 42nd International Film Festival of India (IFFI-2011), in Panaji, Goa on November 30, 2011.jpg\n|bSize = 400\n|cWidth = 190\n|cHeight = 220\n|oTop = 20\n|oLeft = 0\n|Location=center}}\n\n| caption = K.P. Jayasankar, [[International Film Festival of India|IFFI]] ([[42nd International Film Festival of India|2011]])\n| native_name_lang    = Malayalam\n| alma_mater          = [[Maharaja%27s_College,_Ernakulam]], [[Mumbai University ]]\n| birth_place         = [[Ernakulam]], [[Kerala]]\n| occupation          = [[Filmmaker]], [[Educator]], [[Curator]]\n| spouse             = [[Anjali Monteiro]]\n| years_active         = 1991 \u2013 present\n| website = {{url|www.monteiro-jayasankar.com}}  \n}}\n\n'''K.P. Jayasankar''' is a documentary filmmaker and researcher who lives in Mumbai. He is currently Professor at the School of Media and Cultural Studies, [[Tata Institute of Social Sciences]]. Jointly with [[Anjali Monteiro]], he has over thirty-five documentary films and has over 30 national and international awards in film festivals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/poetry-and-harmony-a-delicate-weave-kutch-musicians-anjali-monteiro-and-kp-jayasankar-4951727/|title=A delicate weave of the musical traditions of communities from across Kutch|date=24 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epw.in/author/k-p-jayasankar|title=K P Jayasankar|date=5 June 2015|website=Economic and Political Weekly}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/Their-hearts-take-over-when-the-camera-stops/article15585266.ece|title=Their hearts take over when the camera stops|first=K.|last=Pradeep|date=8 December 2010|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indulgexpress.com/culture/art/2019/jan/05/many-realities-many-worlds-anjali-monteiro--kp-jayasankar-at-the-kochi-biennale-2018-11968.html|title=Many realities, many worlds: Anjali Monteiro & KP Jayasankar at the Kochi Biennale 2018|website=www.indulgexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/anjali-monteiro-425138|title=Anjali Monteiro|website=The Conversation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/a-delicately-woven-musical-journey/articleshow/61327875.cms|title=A delicately woven musical journey &#124; Kochi News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Kochi/documenting-the-social-fabric-of-kutch/article19946084.ece|title=Documenting the social fabric of Kutch|date=30 October 2017|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nJayasankar was born in <nowiki>[[Kochi]]</nowiki>, Kerala, on November 28. He completed his bachelor's degree in chemistry from Maharaja's College, Kochi in 1973 and a master's degree in German studies from Department of Foreign Languages, Mumbai University, in 1982. He has done his Ph.D. in humanities and social sciences from Indian Institute of Technology-Bombay, in 1991. He joined Tata Institute of Social Sciences in 1986. He married his colleague Anjali Monteiro in 1989 and they have a daughter.\nJayasankar joined the Audio-Visual Unit, Tata Institute of Social Sciences, in 1986, which is now the School of Media and Cultural Studies. He has been a visiting faculty/scholar at several media and design schools and universities, in India and overseas, including University of Heidelberg, University of Technology, Sydney, Lund University, Sweden, Goldsmiths University, London and Lahti Institute of Design, Finland.\n\n==Selected publications== \n*2020 Anjali Monteiro, K.P. Jayasankar and Amit Rai, DigiNaka: Subaltern Politics and Digital Media in Post-Capitalist India, Orient Blackswan.<ref>https://orientblackswan.com/EventsInfo?id=9789352879069</ref>\n*2018 Faiz Ullah, Anjali Monteiro and K.P. Jayasankar, DiverCity- Independent Documentary as an Alternate Narrative of the City, in Devasundaram, A.E. (ed) Indian Cinema Beyond Bollywood: The New Independent Cinema Revolution, Routledge\t\n*2016  K.P. Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro, A Fly in The Curry: Independent Documentary in India, Sage, 2016. Won Special Mention [[64th National Film Awards#Golden Lotus Award]] for best book on cinema category.\n*2012 Anjali Monteiro and K.P. Jayasankar, Resisting Censorship in India, East Asia Forum Quarterly, Vol 4, No. 1.\n*2010 Anjali Monteiro K.P. Jayasankar, A New Pair of Scissors- the Draft Cinematograph Bill, Economic and Political Weekly, July 17, 2010\n*2009  K.P. Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro,  Jai Ho Shanghai: The Invisible Poor in Slumdog Millionaire, in Kaldor, Mary et al. (eds) Global Civil Society Yearbook of the London School of Economics, Sage, [[London]]\n*2005 K.P. Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro, Censorship ke Peeche Kya Hai, in Nalini Rajan (ed) Practising Journalism, Sage, [[London]]\n*2003 K.P. Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro, The Plot Thickens \u2013 A Cultural Studies Approach to Media Education in India, in Tony Lavender, Birgitte Tufte and Dafna Lemish (eds.) Global Trends in Media Education, Hampton Press.\n*2001 K.P. Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro, Documentary and Ethnographic Film, Elsevier Encyclopaedia of Social and Behavioural Sciences, Elsevier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/ethnographic-film|title=Ethnographic Film \u2013 an overview &#124; ScienceDirect Topics|website=www.sciencedirect.com}}</ref>\n*2000 K.P. Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro, Between the Normal and the Imaginary \u2013 The Spectator-self, the Other and Satellite Television in India, in Hagen, I and Wasko, J.(eds) Consuming Audiences: Production and Reception in Media Research, Hampton Press.\n*1998 Anjali Monteiro, Official Television and Unofficial Fabrications of the Self: The Spectator as Subject in Nandy, Ashis (ed.), The Secret Politics of  Our Desires, OUP.\n*1993 K.P. Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro, The Spectator-Indian \u2013 An Exploratory Study of the Reception of News, Cultural Studies 10 (1).\n\n==Filmography==\n(Co-directed with [[Anjali Monteiro]]) \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  \"\n! Year !! Title !! Length\n|-\n| 2017 || A Delicate Weave || 62 minutes \n|-\n| 2012 || Farooq vs The State ||25 minutes \n|-\n| 2011 || So Heddan So Hoddan ||60 minutes \n|-\n| 2009 || Do Din ka Mela (A Two Day Fair)  || 60 minutes \n|-\n| 2007 || Our Family   || 56 minutes \n|-\n| 2005 || She Write   || 55 minutes \n|-\n| 2003 || Naata: The Bond  || 45 minutes \n|-\n| 2001 ||Saacha (The Loom)   || 49 minutes\n|-\n| 1997 || YCP 1997  || 43 minutes  \n|-\n| 1995 || Kahankar : Ahankar (Story Maker : Story Taker  || 38 minutes \n|-\n| 1994 ||Identity: The Construction of Selfhood || 20 minutes \n|-\n| 1993 ||A Collective Exploration Of Ourselves, Our Bodies || 23 minutes \n|-\n| 1992 ||One Hundred Years Of Drought || 21 minutes \n|-\n| 1991 ||From the Diary of a Genetic Counsellor || 30 minutes \n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n*2013- Jayasankar's film Saacha (The Loom), co-directed with Anjali Monteiro was a part of the installation, Project Space: Word. Sound. Power. Tate Modern, London, as well as at Kochi-Muziris Biennale.\n*2018 -Around 30 national and international awards to his films include Our Family.\n*2008- Certificate of Merit and Special Mention of the Jury, at MIFF.\n*2013- So Heddan So Hoddan won the Basil \u2013 Wright Award at RAI International Ethnographic Film Festival in\n*2019- A Delicate Weave, which received the Jury's commendation, Intangible culture film prize, 16th Royal Anthropological Institute Festival at Bristol, UK.\n\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|\n[https://theconversation.com/profiles/anjali-monteiro-425138 Anjali Monteiro]\n[https://www.indulgexpress.com/culture/art/2019/jan/05/many-realities-many-worlds-anjali-monteiro--kp-jayasankar-at-the-kochi-biennale-2018-11968.html Many realities, many worlds: Anjali Monteiro & KP Jayasankar at the Kochi Biennale 2018]\n[http://in.sagepub.com/en-in/sas/author/anjali-monteiro Monteiro, Anjali]\n[https://theloftforum.org/people/anjali-monteiro-k-p-jayasankar/ Anjali Monteiro K.P. Jayasankar]\n[https://tiss.edu/view/9/employee/anjali-monteiro/ Prof Anjali Monteiro | Tata Institute of Social Sciences]\n[http://www.indianlink.com.au/filmmakers-anjali-monteiro-and-k-p-jayasankar/ Filmmakers Anjali Monteiro and K P Jayasankar]\n[https://www.socialdifference.columbia.edu/faculty-/anjali-monteiro Anjali Monteiro]\n[https://www.cultureunplugged.com/storyteller/Anjali_Monteiro_and_KP__Jayasankar#/myFilms ]\n[https://scroll.in/reel/855217/in-a-delicate-weave-musicians-from-kutch-stitch-together-a-message-of-love-and-peace In \u2018A Delicate Weave\u2019, musicians from Kutch stitch together a message of love and peace]\n[https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/08949460701424312?journalCode=gvan20 The Bond]\n[https://www.himalmag.com/author/kpjayasankaranjalimonteiro/ K P Jayasankar and Anjali Monteiro, Author at Himal Southasian]\n[https://thewire.in/author/anjali-monteiro-and-kp-dean Anjali Monteiro and KP Dean : Exclusive News Stories by Anjali Monteiro and KP Dean on Current Affairs, Events at The Wire]\n[http://www.raiot.in/author/monteirojaya/ Anjali Monteiro & K. P. Jayasankar, Author at RAIOT]\n[https://www.epw.in/author/anjali-monteiro Anjali Monteiro]\n[https://www.dnaindia.com/topic/anjali-monteiro Anjali Monteiro: Latest News, Videos and Photos on Anjali Monteiro - DNA News]\n[http://www.iicdelhi.nic.in/User_Panel/ProgramDetails.aspx?Value=MnMbKpZavpR6fEUaKULs0zZIhywatnMxHBaLwywmv1FBwHxoroFovaYO09tw9q1fMmC%2F82Pc5Zk%3D IIC| 