ublican}} |'''Chris Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |99,920\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |63%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Mark Setaro\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |54,961\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |35%\n|\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |Carl Peters\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} |[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |2,178\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |1%\n|\n|! style=\"background:#FF7575; \"|Joseph Notarangelo\n|! style=\"background:#FF7575; \"|[[Populist Party (United States, 1984)|Populist]]\n|! style=\"background:#FF7575; \"|1,206\n|! style=\"background:#FF7575; \"|1%\n|*<!--J.M. Carter got 1,034 votes.-->\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1992|1992]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Chris Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |149,095\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |62%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Brian Hughes\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |84,514\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |35%\n|\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |Benjamin Grindlinger\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} |[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |2,984\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |1%\n|\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |Patrick Pasculi\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |2,137\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1%\n|*<!--Two other candidates got less than one percent.-->\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1994|1994]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Chris Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |109,818\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |68%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Ralph Walsh\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |49,537\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |31%\n|\n|{{party shading/Conservative}} |Leonard Marshall\n|{{Party shading/Conservative}} |[[New Jersey Conservative Party|Conservative]]\n|{{party shading/Conservative}} |1,579\n|{{party shading/Conservative}} |1%\n|\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|Arnold Kokans\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|[[Natural Law Party (United States)|Natural Law]]\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|833\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|1%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1996|1996]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Chris Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |146,404\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |64%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Kevin Meara\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |77,565\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |34%\n|\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |Robert Figueroa\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |3,000\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1%\n|\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |J. Morgan Strong\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |2,034\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1%\n|*<!--Arnold Kokans got less than one percent of the vote-->\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1998|1998]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Chris Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |92,991\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |62%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Larry Schneider\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |52,281\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |35%\n|\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |Keith Quarles\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1,753\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1%\n|\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |Morgan Strong\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1,495\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |1%\n|*<!--Nick Mellis got less than one percent of the vote.-->\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 2000|2000]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Chris Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |158,515\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |63%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |[[Reed Gusciora]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |87,956\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |35%\n|\n|{{party shading/Independent}} |Stuart Chaifetz\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{party